The Wall that encompaſſed and went about the ſquare of the holy ground, was of very fair ſtone,Joſ. de Bell. lib. 5. c. 14.
                   and it was five and twenty cubits, or twelve yards and an halfe high, that is, as one ſtood within the compaſſe of it, in the holy ground;

for without it ſtood over a very deep and ſharp precipice, and ſo there was an exceeding great height from the bottome of the trench beneath, to the top of the wall, but within it was no higher then 25 cubits, and that height it carried about the whole ſquare.
